@backup-manager
  backup-manager is a Bash utility script designed to create secure, encrypted archives of critical system directories.
  It automates the process of compressing data, encrypting it with AES256 via GnuPG, and managing disk space by rotating old backups.
  
  #Features
    -Secure AES256 Encryption: Utilizes GPG symmetric encryption with a dedicated passphrase file for high-level data protection.
    -Automated Directory Archiving: Packages multiple system paths into compressed .tar.gz format.
    -Smart Retention Policy: Automatically maintains a clean environment by keeping only the 3 most recent backups and removing older archives.
    -Comprehensive Logging: Redirects all standard output and errors to /var/log/backup-manager.log for detailed audit trails.
    -Performance Tracking: Calculates and logs the exact duration of the backup process in seconds using high-precision timestamps.
  
  #How It Works
    The script executes a streamlined pipeline: it first validates the destination path, then streams a compressed tarball directly into a GPG encryption process to ensure data is never stored unencrypted.
    It captures the execution exit code to verify success before checking the backup count. If more than 3 archives exist, it identifies the oldest file using a time-sorted list (ls -tr) and deletes it to prevent storage overflow.
  
  #Decryption
    -To restore your data, you must use GPG to decrypt the .gpg file back into a compressed archive.
    -Run the following command (replace FILENAME with your actual backup file):
    gpg --batch --passphrase-file [password path] --decrypt FILENAME.tar.gz.gpg > restored_backup.tar.gz
    -Once decrypted, you can extract the contents using: tar -xzf restored_backup.tar.gz
  
  #Configuration
    -Password Management: The encryption passphrase must be stored in a plain text file named password located in the same directory as the script.
    -Security Setup: For production environments, you must change the file owner to the root user and restrict permissions to prevent unauthorized access:
    sudo chown root:root backup-manager.sh password
    sudo chmod 700 backup-manager.sh password
    -Service Customization: To change which files or folders are archived, you must manually add them to the directories_to_backup array inside the backup-manager.sh file.
    -How to Edit: Open the script in a text editor (e.g., nano) and update the list:
    directories_to_backup=( '/etc' '/var/www' '/home/user/docs' )
    -Log & Backup Paths: The destination for archives (path) and the log file (log_path) can be adjusted directly in the variable definitions section of the script.
